%  EXERCISE 3.14
% =============================================================
\exercise{3.14}

Give the best lower bound that you can for the following code fragment, as a function of the initial value of $n$.
\begin{verbatim}
  while (n > 1)
    if (ODD(n))
      n = 3 * n + 1;
    else
      n = n / 2;
\end{verbatim}

\textbf{Answer:} This code calculates the sequence of the famous Collatz conjecture. We are asked for the best \textit{lower bound} ($\Omega$) for its execution time.

To find the minimum possible number of iterations, we consider the scenario where $n$ decreases to $1$ as fast as mathematically possible. The condition \texttt{n = n / 2} halves the value, whereas the condition \texttt{n = 3 * n + 1} more than triples it. Thus, the fastest path to $1$ occurs when $n$ is always EVEN (i.e., $n$ is initially a power of $2$, $n = 2^k$).

If $n = 2^k$, the \texttt{else} block will be executed exactly $k$ times until $n=1$. The number of iterations is $k = \log_2 n$.

Since the number of iterations can never be fewer than $\log_2 n$ (it cannot decrease faster than halving at each step), the best lower bound for the execution of this code fragment is:
\[
    \boxed{\Omega(\log n)}
\]

